<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-02-14T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-02-14T13:00:00-05:00" n="473" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d473">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/161: Telegram</note>
                                <head>
                                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Long</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                            State</gloss>
                                    </hi>
                                </head>
                                <opener>
                                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg>
                                </opener>
                                <opener>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                                        <placeName>
                                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-02-14T19:00:00+01:00">February 14, 1935—7 p.m.</date>
                                        <lb/> [Received February 14—3:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p>72. My 69, February 13, noon.<note n="9" xml:id="d473fn9">Not
                                        printed.</note> Recent information all points to a more
                                    general preparation for an extensive campaign in Abyssinia than
                                    was indicated by the announcements of the Italian Government.
                                    Military forces and supplies are being moved clandestinely.
                                    Every effort is being made to prevent information of the size or
                                    general nature of the shipments. Troops called are kept in
                                    barracks and denied freedom. Movements are by night.</p>
                                <p>I am today advised by a person I believe well informed that
                                    30,000 troops have left the port of Naples; that the movement
                                    now under way contemplates between 200,000 and 300,000 troops
                                    being used in Ethiopia; and that the troops who are now or who
                                    have been recently in Tripoli and thus have had tropical
                                    experience are being transferred to the Ethiopian front and are
                                    being replaced by forces from Italy.</p>
                                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                                <closer>
                                    <signed>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Long</hi>
                                    </signed>
                                </closer>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>